W. 124th Street, west from and across Morningside Avenue. The buildings at the left are the property of John D. Rockefeller Jr. and are about to be demolished according to the New York Times of October 5th, 1938. Opposite same is the 2 story business structure that was recently demolished and the site included in the new Station "F" Post Office that bears No. 2 LaSalle Street.

September 1928.

Geo. L. Balgue

Morningside Avenue, west side, south from W. 124th Street, showing a row of tenements between 123rd to 124th Streets. South of same is Morningside Park. The westerly margin of the latter is Morningside Drive with numerous apartment houses upon same.
View No. 2 is the same area at a latter date and shows the absence of tenements exclusive of that at the S.W. corner of 124th Street. This, according to the New York Times of October 5th, 1938, is shortly to follow; being included in demolition of structures owned by John D. Rockefeller and consisting of No's. 400 to 432 W. 124th Street. Subsequently the only remaining building in the lower half of this block will be the Lincoln School on 123rd Street.

June 1930
View 2: April 1, 1938.

Geo. L. Balgue
P. L. Sperr

West 124th Street, west from Morningside Avenue, showing a 2 story structure adjoining the N.W. corner which will be included in the new site of Station "F", United States Post Office according to the New York Times of March 22, 1938. This structure, formerly occupied by the Willard Storage Battery Company extends thru the block to front on La Salle Place. This office is now located at No. 309-11 W. 125th Street and from which it will shortly remove to this location (No. 2-4 La Salle Place). Views 2 and 3 are eastward views of the same area.

May 4, 1938.
Views 1,2 and 3.

P. L. Sperr
